## Translations

### Architecture

This codebase uses a hybrid translation system that combines:

- **JSON fallback file** (`src/lib/i18n/translations.json`) - Static translations for development
- **Database translations** (`translation` table) - Dynamic translations that override JSON (loaded via `+layout.server.ts`)

Translations are automatically loaded in the root layout and made available to all pages through `page.data.translations`.

### Supported Languages

Currently supported languages:

- `'ro'` - Romanian (default)
- `'en'` - English

### Database Schema

Translations are stored in the `translation` table:

```typescript
export const translation = pgTable("translation", {
  id: serial("id").primaryKey(),
  key: varchar("key", { length: 255 }).notNull(), // e.g., 'contact.title'
  language: varchar("language", { length: 10 }).notNull(), // 'ro', 'en'
  value: text("value").notNull(),
  createdAt: timestamp("created_at", { withTimezone: true, mode: "date" })
    .notNull()
    .defaultNow(),
  updatedAt: timestamp("updated_at", { withTimezone: true, mode: "date" })
    .notNull()
    .defaultNow(),
});
```

### Loading Translations

Translations are loaded in the root layout server file:

```typescript
// src/routes/[[lang=lang]]/+layout.server.ts
import type { LayoutServerLoad } from "./$types";
import { loadTranslations } from "$lib/server/translations";

export const load: LayoutServerLoad = async (event) => {
  const translations = await loadTranslations();

  return {
    user: event.locals.user,
    translations,
  };
};
```

The `loadTranslations()` function:

1. Fetches all translations from the database
2. Converts flat records (e.g., `key: 'contact.title'`) into nested objects
3. Returns a structure matching `translations.json` format
4. Falls back to empty structure if no DB translations exist (JSON will be used)

### Using Translations in Components

#### Basic Usage

Import the `t` function from `$lib/i18n/index.svelte`:

```svelte
<script lang="ts">
  import { page } from '$app/state';
  import { t } from '$lib/i18n/index.svelte';

  // Get current language from route params
  const language = $derived((page.params?.lang || 'ro') as 'ro' | 'en');
</script>

<h1>{t('contact.title')}</h1>
<p>{t('contact.description')}</p>
```

#### With Fallback Values

Always provide fallback text for better developer experience:

```svelte
<h1>{t('contact.title') || 'Contact Us'}</h1>
<p>{t('contact.description') || 'Get in touch with us'}</p>
```

#### Nested Keys

Use dot notation for nested translation keys:

```svelte
<!-- translations.json structure: -->
<!-- {
  "ro": {
    "contact": {
      "hero": {
        "title": "GET IN TOUCH"
      }
    }
  }
} -->

<h1>{t('contact.hero.title') || 'GET IN TOUCH'}</h1>
```

#### Placeholder Replacement

Use `{{placeholder}}` syntax in translations and pass replacements:

```svelte
<script lang="ts">
  import { t } from '$lib/i18n/index.svelte';

  const userName = $state('John');
  const itemCount = $state(5);
</script>

<!-- Translation: "Hello {{name}}, you have {{count}} items" -->
<p>{t('greeting.message', { name: userName, count: itemCount })}</p>
```

#### SEO Meta Tags

Use translations in `<svelte:head>` for SEO:

```svelte
<script lang="ts">
  import { page } from '$app/state';
  import { t } from '$lib/i18n/index.svelte';

  const language = $derived((page.params?.lang || 'ro') as 'ro' | 'en');
</script>

<svelte:head>
  <title>{t('contact-page.title') || 'GET IN TOUCH'}</title>
  <meta name="description" content={t('contact-page.description') || 'Contact us'} />
  <meta property="og:title" content={t('contact-page.title') || 'GET IN TOUCH'} />
  <meta property="og:description" content={t('contact-page.description') || 'Contact us'} />
  <meta property="og:image" content={t('contact-page.image') || ''} />
  <meta property="og:url" content={page.url.toString()} />
  <meta property="og:type" content="website" />
  <meta property="og:site_name" content={t('site.name') || 'Sakura'} />
  <meta property="og:locale" content={language} />
</svelte:head>
```

#### Language Detection

The current language is automatically determined from the route parameter:

```svelte
<script lang="ts">
  import { page } from '$app/state';

  // Language from route: /ro/contact or /en/contact
  const language = $derived((page.params?.lang || 'ro') as 'ro' | 'en');
</script>
```

The `t` function automatically uses the current language from `page.params.lang`. If a translation key is missing in the current language, it falls back to Romanian (`'ro'`).

### Translation Key Naming Convention

Use descriptive, hierarchical keys:

- **Page-level keys**: `contact.title`, `menu.title`, `landing.hero.title`
- **Component-level keys**: `contact-hero.title`, `contact-hero.description`
- **Common keys**: `common.loading`, `common.error`, `site.name`
- **SEO keys**: `contact-page.title`, `contact-page.description`, `contact-page.image`

### Example: Complete Page with Translations

```svelte
<script lang="ts">
  import { page } from '$app/state';
  import { t } from '$lib/i18n/index.svelte';
  import { Button } from '$lib/components/ui/button';
  import { Input } from '$lib/components/ui/input';

  const language = $derived((page.params?.lang || 'ro') as 'ro' | 'en');

  let name = $state('');
  let loading = $state(false);
  let error = $state<string | null>(null);
</script>

<svelte:head>
  <title>{t('contact-page.title') || 'GET IN TOUCH'}</title>
  <meta name="description" content={t('contact-page.description') || 'Contact us'} />
  <meta property="og:locale" content={language} />
</svelte:head>

<div class="container mx-auto my-24">
  <h1 class="text-5xl font-light">
    {t('contact-hero.title') || 'GET IN TOUCH'}
  </h1>

  <form
    onsubmit={(e) => {
      e.preventDefault();
      // Handle submit...
    }}
  >
    <Input
      placeholder={t('contact.form.name') || 'Name'}
      bind:value={name}
    />

    <Button type="submit" disabled={loading}>
      {loading
        ? (t('common.loading') || 'Loading...')
        : (t('contact.send-message') || 'Send Message')
      }
    </Button>
  </form>

  {#if error}
    <p class="text-red-500">{error}</p>
  {/if}
</div>
```

### Managing Translations

#### Adding Translations to Database

Translations can be added/updated in the database through:

- Admin interface (if available)
- Direct database operations
- Migration scripts

#### Translation Key Format

Store keys in the database using dot notation:

- `contact.title` → `{ "contact": { "title": "..." } }`
- `contact-hero.description1` → `{ "contact-hero": { "description1": "..." } }`

The `loadTranslations()` function automatically converts flat keys into nested objects.

### Best Practices

1. **Always provide fallbacks** - Use `t('key') || 'Fallback text'` pattern
2. **Use consistent naming** - Follow the hierarchical key structure
3. **Group related translations** - Use prefixes like `contact-`, `menu-`, `landing-`
4. **Translate all user-facing text** - Never hardcode text in components
5. **Use translations in SEO tags** - Always translate meta tags and Open Graph data
6. **Test both languages** - Verify translations work for both `'ro'` and `'en'`
7. **Keep JSON file updated** - Maintain `translations.json` as a fallback
8. **Use placeholders for dynamic content** - Use `{{placeholder}}` syntax for variables
9. **Access language reactively** - Use `$derived` to get language from `page.params.lang`
10. **Handle missing translations gracefully** - Fallback to Romanian, then to the key itself

